15 minutes 

FREE

The goal of this Lab

In this quick tutorial, you will learn how to:

 

  • Create an Amazon Web Services (AWS) account; the single sign-in identity or AWS account root user has complete access to all AWS services and resources in the account. 
  • Explore AWS Product offerings and pricing tiers. 
  • Create an AWS Budgets with Thresholds
  • Analyze costs associated with your usage.

 

The outcome of this Lab

At the completion of this Lab, you will be able to start working on your AWS labs within the free tier offerings.

If your free tier is already expired, you will find the estimated costs per lab in the cover sheet.

Our aim is to remain within the free offerings or keep costs below $1 for all labs.

 

We hope you will have a pleasant learning journey. 

 

Regards,

The Training team.

 

 DISCLAIMER: 

This Check Point Hands-on lab doesn’t automatically authorize you to expense the costs or experiment with different AWS services and CloudGuard product deployments. 

We will include cost calculations for each lab, but like the Shared Responsibility Model, you remain responsible for cost control of the cloud resources.

 

For expense approval, consult your management.

  

 

Explore the AWS Free Tier

 

Goal

:

In this section, you will explore the different pricing tiers of the AWS product categories and perform a pricing estimate.

Outcome

:

At the completion of this section, you will be able to estimate costs across the AWS products and services.

 

This lab is based on the online AWS getting started guide:

https://aws.amazon.com/getting-started/hands-on/control-your-costs-free-tier-budgets/

 

Access the Free Tier page

Browse to the AWS Free tier Page

Screenshot 1 – AWS Free Tier home page

Explore 12 month free offers

1. Scroll down below to the “Free Tier Details.

2. Under the “Tier Type” filter, tick the following checkboxes

Filter (check):

Tier Type

: 12 months free

Product Categories

: Compute

 

You should see that you have 750 hours of free compute per month of Linux, RHEL, or SLES t2.micro or t3.micro instance dependent on region.

 

Screenshot 2 – AWS Free tier- EC2 and ELB

 

Navigate to the Amazon Marketplace to look at a Free Tier application called “LAMP.”

 

Screenshot 3 – LAMP in Market Place is part of Free Tier

 

Read the description in the Total Price window.

Many vendors offer products through the Amazon marketplace that are part of the Free Tier. However the product will be based upon vendor recommended sizing of your virtual server (Instance type); in this case the instance type “t3a.small”.

 This recommended sizing’s in general fall outside the free tier; you will have to explicitly select a t2.micro or t3.micro instance during the launch!

Tier Type

Product Categories

Read the Free Tier description for S3. You have 5 GB of Standard Storage with 20,000 Get Requests and 2,000 Put Requests.

Sign-up with AWS (or Sign-in)

 

Goal

:

Create an AWS account as a “root” user and explore the AWS Management Console.

Outcome

:

At the completion of this section, you will be able to access all AWS Products and Services for the creation of Labs and BluePrints.

 

IMPORTANT

To create your AWS account you will need to provide a username and your personal details.

A personal credit card is required for approval.

Sign-up

1. Navigate in your browser to the AWS Account sign-up page

Complete the Sign-up wizard to create your account:

Enter Email & Password, Account name, and click “Continue”

 

 

Screenshot 12 – Email, Password, Account name


 Complete your contact information and click “Create Account and Continue”

Screenshot 13 – Contact information


 Select the Basic Plan.

Screenshot 14 – Support Plan

 Complete your payment information and final steps to create your Account:

Screenshot 15 – Payment Information 

 Wait for the congratulations from AWS.  You have now signed-up with AWS.

 Sign-in

 Once your account is approved, start the sign-in as “Root user” with your email address.

Screenshot 16 – AWS Sign-in screen

 Enter your root user “Password” in the “Root user sign-in” page

Screenshot 17 – AWS Sign-in Root user sign in

 In the Management Console verify your Region in the right upper corner and click “Services” in the left upper corner.

 

Screenshot 18 - Region North Virginia

Review your spend and Free Tier usage

 

Goal

:

To make you familiar with the AWS Billing Console to review your overall AWS spend and Free Tier usage.

Outcome

:

At the completion of this section, you will be able to interpret the Billing Dashboard and analyze your daily, monthly, and yearly usage in the cloud.

 

What you should know about “AWS Billing and Cost Management”

AWS Billing and Cost Management is the service that you use to pay your AWS bill, monitor your usage, and analyze and control your costs.

AWS automatically charges the credit card that you provided when you signed up for a new account with AWS. Charges appear on your monthly credit card bill.

 

Access your billing dashboard

1. Sign-in to the AWS Management Console with your root account credentials.

Click on your Account Name and select “My Billing Dashboard”

Screenshot 21 – AWS management console – Account Name options

Review your billing dashboard

 

1. Once you reach the Billing & Cost Management Dashboard page, view a summary of your month-to-date costs in the Spend Summary section, as well as a service-based breakdown in the Month-to-Date Spend by Service section.

 

Screenshot 22 – Billing Dashboard

Analyze top free tier service usage

 

Examine the Top Free Tier Services by Usage pane to see an overview of what part of your usage falls into the Free Tier,  This pane highlights the highest percentage of month-to-date usage against Free Tier limits categorized by service.

Screenshot 23 – Top Free Tier Services by usage

 

  1. Look at the “Important Information about these costs” pane of the Billing Dashboard.
  2. Look at the Amazon S3 usage.
  3. Look at the Free Tier usage limit column; it outlines the Free Tier discount. In this example, the Free Tier gives you the first 2,000 S3 Put Requests for free.
  4. Look at the Month-to-date usage column; it shows the percentage of the Free Tier benefit you have used this month. In this example, exactly 2,000 Put Requests to S3 have been made (100% of the Free Tier limit), which means any additional usage in excess of this limit will be billed at normal AWS prices.

NOTE: If your free tier has expired you may find a different overview.

Access all your Free Tier usage

 

Click the “View all” button in the top right corner of the Top Free Tier Service by Usage widget.

This will provide more details into your Free Tier-eligible usage.

NOTE: if your free tier is expired you will not see this information.

 

 

Screenshot 24 – View all

Analyze all your Free Tier usage

Look at the On the All Free Tier services by usage page; all of your usage for all services in the Free Tier are listed. In addition to your month-to-date actual usage, how much service usage you are forecasted to have by the end of the month is detailed in the Month-end forecasted usage column.

In the example in the screenshot to the right, note that your forecasted usage of S3 Put requests is 6,000. Exceeding the limit of the Free Tier generally results in a billable charge.

NOTE: if your free tier is expired you will not see this information. 

 

 

Screenshot 25 – All Free Tier services by usage


Modify your AWS Free Tier Usage Limit email alerts

 

Select “Billing Preferences” from the left navigation bar to change who gets the email alerts 

To opt other people into receiving Free Tier Usage Alerts, in the Email Address field add their email address and choose Save preferences.

 By default, most accounts are automatically opted into receiving AWS Free Tier Usage Limit email alerts when their service usage exceeds 85% of a given Free Tier usage limit.

 

Screenshot 26 – Set Billing preferences

Set up a cost budget

 

Goal

:

To set up a cost budget in the AWS Billing Console using AWS Budgets.

Outcome

:

At the completion of this section, you will be able to set guard rails on your spending and budget to avoid unexpected payments.

 

As part of your cost budget, you will set up three notifications: 

  1. one for if your costs reach 50% of your budget,
  2. one for if your costs are forecasted to exceed your budget, 
  3. one if your costs do exceed your budget.

 We will follow the four steps in the budget wizard:

  1. select budget type
  2. set your budget
  3. configure thresholds
  4. confirm budget

Select budget type

 

  1. From the navigation menu on the left, select Budgets then select Create a budget. On the Create budget page, choose Cost as the Budget Type.

 

Screenshot 27 – Budget

Select Cost budget and continue to “Set your Budget”.

Screenshot 28 – Cost Budget

 Set your budget

 Set your budget details, including your budgeted amount. From there, you can refine your budget using the optional budget parameters.

 

Name

MyMonthlyBudget”

Period 

Monthly

Budget Effective dates

Expiring budget

 

Screenshot 29 – Set your Budget

 1. Set monthly Budget:

 

Type

Budget Effective dates

$5

 

Screenshot 30 – Specify your monthly Budget

 

  1. In “Advanced Options” choose defaults and click “Configure thresholds”.

Screenshot 31 – Advanced Options

Configure thresholds

 Configure this notification to notify you when actual costs are 50% of the budgeted amount.

 

Threshold-based on actual costs:

Based on

: actual costs

Alert Threshold

Email recipients

  1. Add another threshold by clicking on  “+ New threshold”.

Screenshot 32 – Thresholds; Actual costs

 1. Configure this notification to notify you when actual costs are greater than 100% of the budgeted amount.

Screenshot 33 – Thresholds; Forecast

                               

Configure this notification to notify you when actual costs are greater than 100% of the budgeted amount.

Complete the Budget creation with “Confirm”. 

If the “confirm” fails make sure that you have removed any budget actions that require IAM policy or other actions.

Screenshot 34 – Thresholds; Forecast

 If all settings are ok, proceed to create.

Screenshot 35 – Budget details

Review your new budget

 
Look at the newly created budget in the overview of your AWS budgets.

AWS TIP:

It is a best practice to create a total monthly cost budget for each AWS account that you use.

You can create up to 62 budget days per month using the AWS Budgets service within the Free Tier limit. After that, you simply pay as you go to create additional budgets.

 

Screenshot 36 – Budget overview

Inspect your new budget

 

Select your budget to review your budget details.

From there, you can view your budget details, access a budget performance summary, and inspect your historical budget performance.

 

Screenshot 37 – Budget details


Lab Summary

At the completion of this Lab you now have successfully created:

  1. Your AWS Account
  2. Your Root credentials
  3. Your Cost Budget
  4. Thresholds to monitor your costs versus your budget.

At the completion of the lab the Learner will:

  • Have knowledge of the different pricing tiers in the AWS product Categories.
  • Be able to perform a pricing estimate.
  • Have knowledge of the navigation options in the AWS Management Console.
  • Be able to interpret the Billing Dashboard and analyze daily, monthly, and yearly usage in the cloud.
  • Be able to set guard rails on your spending and budget to avoid unexpected payments.
